explanation:
For checking the MISRA rule about using const-qualified pointee types, the analyzer needs the exact types and signatures involved when pointers are created, returned or passed. Reason for each symbol:

- OS_timebase_internal_record_t (type/struct definition): The function declares timebase as OS_timebase_internal_record_t * and writes to its fields (nominal_start_time, nominal_interval_time). The struct definition is required to confirm which members are modified and therefore whether the pointee must be non-const.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro definition): This macro produces the pointer assigned to timebase. Its expansion determines the exact pointer type returned (e.g., whether it yields a pointer-to-non-const or pointer-to-const) and any casts that affect constness analysis.

- OS_timebase_table (global object/table declaration): The table's declared element type (array of OS_timebase_internal_record_t or const-qualified elements) influences whether the pointer returned by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET can/should be const-qualified.

- OS_object_token_t (typedef/definition): The local variable token is the object-token type; its definition is needed to know whether passing &token yields a pointer-to-const or pointer-to-non-const and whether functions that take token pointers could accept const-qualified tokens.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById (prototype/signature): This function produces token (by output parameter). Its signature shows the expected type of the token output parameter and whether the token must be mutable; this affects whether &token usage would require a non-const pointer.

- OS_TimeBaseLock_Impl (prototype/signature): Called with &token; the parameter type (OS_object_token_t * vs const OS_object_token_t *) is needed to see if the API requires a mutable token pointer or could accept a const-qualified pointee.

- OS_TimeBaseSet_Impl (prototype/signature): Called with &token and also the function that sets the time base internals. Its parameter types determine whether the token pointer must be non-const and whether the function itself modifies the underlying timebase (in which case the timebase pointer must be non-const).

- OS_TimeBaseUnlock_Impl (prototype/signature): Same rationale as Lock_Impl — its parameter type determines whether &token requires a non-const pointer.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease (prototype/signature): Called with &token; its parameter type is needed to determine if it expects to modify the token (non-const) or could accept a const pointer.

Together these symbols let the analyzer determine: (a) the exact type of the timebase pointer returned/used and whether its pointee is modified (hence whether it must be non-const), and (b) whether token pointers passed to callees require non-const pointers or could be const-qualified. Without these declarations/signatures the const-qualification decisions cannot be reliably made.
